07808nam a22009255i 9781487574468DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20201991onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875744687 a10.3138/97814875744682doi  a(DE-B1597)549340  a(OCoLC)1153532070  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a342.71/0322000aOptions for a New Canada /ced. by Ronald Watts, Douglas Brown. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4c©1991  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD -- tINTRODUCTORY STATEMENT -- tINTRODUCTORY STATEMENT -- tACKNOWLEDGEMENTS -- tNOTES ABOUT THE AUTHORS -- tI. Introduction -- t1. An Overview -- tII. An Outline of the Options -- t2. Canada's Constitutional Options: An Outline -- tIII. The Context -- t3. The Context for Future Constitutional Options -- t4. Shared and Divergent Values -- t5. Constitutional Change and the Three Equalities -- tIV. Basic Options and Processes -- t6. Quebec Beyond the Federal Regime of 1867-1982: From Distinct Society to National Community -- t7. Options for the Future of Canada: the Good, the Bad, and the Fantastic -- t8. Towards a New Constitutional Process -- t9. Riding the Constitutional Rollercoaster: A Commentary -- t10. Alternative Methods for Aboriginal Participation in Processes of Constitutional Reform -- tV. Models for Future Structures -- t11. European Integration: Are There Lessons for Canada? -- t12. Other Federal and Nonfederal Countries: Lessons for Canada -- tVI. Areas of Adjustinent -- t13. Constitutional Design in a Federation: An Economist's Perspective -- t14. Distribution of Functions and Jurisdiction: A Political Scientist's Analysis -- t15. Equality or Asymmetry: Why Choose? -- t16. The Federative Superstructure -- t17. Areas of Adjustment: A Lawyer's Perspective0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe sharp and overwhelming reaction in Quebec to the failure of the Meech Lake Accord has been unprecedented public support for sovereignty and practically no support for the current form of Canadian federalism. This has led to renewed demands for a major constitutional restructuring which, if unsuccessful, is likely this time around to result in the separation of Quebec from Canada. At the same time there is considerable pressure from many other quarters in Canada for other sorts of constitutional change, such as Senate reform and aboriginal self-government. There are also calls for Canadian federalism to be modernized to provide a more effective political response to the global challenges of the contemporary world. Recognizing that Canada is facing a renewed and potentially disastrous constitutional impasse, the Business Council on National Issues has commissioned the papers in this book to provide a fresh analysis of our difficult constitutional problems. The contributors include some of Canada’s leading academic commentators in the fields of political science, economics, philosophy and law. These papers do not provide a single blueprint for Canada’s future; rather they present a range of possible solution and arrangements, each with attendant opportunities and risks. Among the alternatives explored are a restructured federalism, a looser federal union with strong provinces, and an arrangement called “asymmetrical federalism” which would treat Quebec differently than the other nine provinces. Other options include looser forms of confederal economic union, and the possible separation of Canada into two or more independent successor-states. Choosing among the alternatives will not be easy, but the message of these papers is that if Canadians do not now weigh the alternatives carefully and decide what they want, the options will narrow and could produce unintended and undesired results. The choice is up to Canadians.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aConstitutional amendmentszCanada. 0aFederal governmentzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aBoadway, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Douglas M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Douglas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCairns, Alan C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCourchene, Thomas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGagnon, Alain-G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkes, David C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaforest, Guy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeslie, Peter M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDougall, John N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeekison, J. Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilne, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonahan, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorse, Bradford W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRussell, Peter H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaint-Pierre, Guy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoberman, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStinson, William W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwinton, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Charles, econtributor.4ctb